{"attack":true,"case":"The target violates STANDARD std-crit-design clause (1) and clause (2) via a units mismatch between its stated mechanism and its forbidden cases, and the violation is non-trivial because it determines whether the forbidden cases are even computable by the repository's harness.\n\n(1) The mechanism's benefit equation is written in per-question units: Net benefit = recall_wrong * p_wrong_majority - FPR_right * p_right_majority, where p_wrong_majority and p_right_majority are fractions of questions. Multiplying a rate (recall_wrong) by a fraction of questions yields 'questions fixed per question,' a per-question quantity. This is the quantity the mechanism claims governs whether filtering strictly improves aggregate accuracy.\n\n(2) The third forbidden case is stated in those same per-question units: 'recall_wrong * p_wrong_majority - FPR_right * p_right_majority is negative while harness accuracy exceeds self-consistency.' But the first two forbidden cases switch to a different, unexplained unit: 'harness accuracy <= self-consistency accuracy on >= 60% of questions in that regime' and '>= 50% of questions.' A per-question percentage of questions where harness accuracy <= self-consistency accuracy is not the same quantity as the per-question net-benefit equation in the mechanism. A 60%-of-questions threshold on a per-question comparison is not derivable from a net-benefit equation whose terms are rates multiplied by question-fractions.\n\nBecause the proposal never states the mapping between the per-question net-benefit quantity and the %-of-questions thresholds (60%, 50%), the forbidden cases are not stated in the same measurable quantities as the mechanism. A proposal whose forbidden cases are expressed in units that cannot be obtained by evaluating the mechanism's named equation violates clause (2) of std-crit-design, and the violation is concrete: a re-runner computing recall_wrong * p_wrong_majority - FPR_right * p_right_majority from the harness output cannot, without an unstated conversion rule, decide whether the 60% / 50% per-question thresholds have been crossed.","counterexample":null}